# kit-manifest — the harness-kit SHIP CONTRACT: the single declarative source
# for which files the kit installs, which ownership layer each belongs to, and
# which previously-shipped paths are retired. install-lib.sh derives every
# file set from this file (there are no hard-coded inventory lists); the
# drift checks (#9c/#9d) derive manifest-completeness from it; the kit's
# update mode reads the NEW kit's copy to decide what to replace, add, and
# remove.
#
# Format: one entry per line —
#   <layer> <repo-relative path> [src=<path under the kit's scripts/ tree>]
# Fields are whitespace-separated; '#' lines and blank lines are ignored.
# src= names the template source when it differs from the default derivation
# (strip the leading `scripts/` from the path). content entries use
# dest= the other way around: their path is template-relative and dest=
# names the installed location — they are authored/copied by the SKILL's
# init flow, never by the installer.
#
# Layers:
#   mechanism        Copied verbatim at init; update REPLACES it while the
#                    installed copy still matches its integrity pin.
#   policy           Template copied at init, owned by the repo after: update
#                    only ever DIFFS it, even when pristine and unmarked.
#   optional-policy  Authored per repo (never copied from the kit); when
#                    present it is integrity-pinned and diff-only, like policy.
#   retired          No longer shipped. Update REMOVES the installed copy only
#                    when it is pristine (sha still matches its pin) and not
#                    '# tailored'; drifted or tailored copies are kept and
#                    reported for manual review — retirement never deletes
#                    local changes.
#
# This file is itself mechanism: integrity-pinned in
# scripts/harness/.harness-manifest and protected by guard-config.sh — it
# tells update what to overwrite and delete, which makes it the most
# security-sensitive shipped file after the integrity manifest. Ship a new
# file by adding its line here; stop shipping one by MOVING its line to the
# retired layer (never just deleting the line).

